[Several species of the genus _Perkinsus_ are responsible for causing perkinsosis in molluscs such as oysters, mussels, clams, and abalone worldwide. _Perkinsus olseni_ is the only species known to cause this disease in the Asia-Pacific region and is responsible for perkinsosis in abalone, clams, and pearl oysters. _P. atlanticus_ is a junior synonym of _P. olseni_ (http://tinyurl.com/k7ngn3e).

The following information was obtained from the Canadian Food Inspection Agency's Fact Sheet on Infection with _P. olseni_, http://tinyurl.com/og6oerr:

"_Perkinsus olseni_ causes death in juvenile and adult molluscs. Overall mortality is 30-40 per cent in molluscs that are 3-4 cm long.

Infected molluscs may exhibit any of the following signs:
- behavior: gaping
- appearance: decreased rate of growth; brown, pus-filled spots in the foot, gills and mantle; retracted mantle; very thin body; pale digestive gland.

The causal agent of _P. olseni_ is not a risk to human health."

The New Zealand green-lipped mussel, (_Perna canaliculus_), also known as the New Zealand mussel, the greenshell mussel, kuku, and kutai, is a bivalve mollusc in the family Mytilidae, the true mussels. _P. canaliculus_ has great importance as a cultivated species in New Zealand (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perna_canalicula).

A photo of New Zealand green-lipped mussels (_Perna canaliculus_) can be seen at http://tinyurl.com/mpe4tok. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2744165,12678.]
